'''Old Serbia''' ({{lang-sr|Стара Србија}} / ''Stara Srbija'') is a Serbian term<ref name="Radovanović2004">{{cite book|author=Milovan Radovanović|title=Etnički i demografski procesi na Kosovu i Metohiji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AKotAQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Liber Press|page=33}}</ref> used for the territory which according to some Serbian authors formed the core of medieval [[Serbia]].{{sfn|Dedijer|2000}} It included the regions of [[Raška (region)|Raška]], [[Kosovo and Metohija]] and the northwestern part of [[Macedonia (region)|Macedonia]].<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=KfqbujXqQBkC&pg=PA38|title=The National Question in Yugoslavia: Origins, History, Politics|author=Ivo Banač|publisher=Cornell University Press|year=1988|isbn=978-0801494932|page=38}}</ref> The Slavic population of this territory was referred to as '''Old Serbians''' ({{lang-sr|Старосрбијанци}} / ''Starosrbijanci'').{{sfn|Sebright|Irby|1877}}

==Etymology==
[[Vuk Stefanović Karadžić]] referred to "Old Serbia" as a territory of the Serb people that was part of [[medieval Serbia]] prior to the [[Ottoman conquest of the Balkans|Ottoman conquest]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Vladimir Stojančević|title=Vuk Karadžić i njegovo doba: rasprave i članci|year=1988|publisher=Zavod za udžbenike i nastavna sredstva}}</ref>  The term originated in Serbian common speech and was introduced by the refugees of the [[Great Serb Migrations]]<ref name="Radovanovic-38">{{cite book|author=Milovan Radovanović|title=Etnički i demografski procesi na Kosovu i Metohiji|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=AKotAQAAIAAJ|year=2004|publisher=Liber Press|page=38}}</ref> who lived in territories of the [[Habsburg Monarchy]]. 
{{Multiple image
 | direction = vertical
 | width     = 200
 | image1    = Petrova crkva 4.jpg
 | caption1  = [[Church of the Holy Apostles Peter and Paul, Ras|Church of St. Peter]] in [[Raška (region)|Raška]]
 | image2    = Medieval Novo Brdo Fortress after reconstruction.jpg
 | caption2  = [[Novo Brdo Fortress]] in [[Kosovo]]
 | image3    = Маркови - кули - Прилеп.JPG
 | caption3  = [[Markovi Kuli|Marko's Towers]] in [[Republic of Macedonia|Macedonia]]
}}

It re-emerged in the aspirations of liberating these areas during the time of the [[Serbian Revolution]] and would later designate the areas to the south not yet liberated by 1833 and 1878.

==History==

In May 1877 a delegation of Serbs of Old Serbia presented their request to the government of Serbia to 'liberate' and unite Old Serbia with the [[Principality of Serbia]].{{sfn|Mitrović|1996|p=68}} They also informed representatives of the [[Great Powers]] and [[Emperor of Russia]] about their demands.{{sfn|Mitrović|1996|p=68}} In the same year the Committee for the Liberation of Old Serbia and Macedonia was founded.<ref name="SrejovićGavrilović1983">{{cite book|author1=Dragoslav Srejović|author2=Slavko Gavrilović|author3=Sima M. Ćirković|title=Istorija srpskog naroda: knj. Od Berlinskog kongresa do Ujedinjenja 1878-1918 (2 v.)|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L75BAAAAYAAJ|accessdate=21 May 2013|year=1983|publisher=Srpska književna zadruga|page=291}}</ref> In the 1877 peace after the [[Serbian-Turkish Wars (1876-1878)]], the Serbs hoped to gain the [[Kosovo Vilayet]] and [[Sanjak of Novi Pazar]] to the [[Lim (river)|Lim river]].{{sfn|Jelavich|1983b|p=29}}  However, with the [[Treaty of Berlin (1878)|Treaty of Berlin]] they received full sovereignty and made territorial gains around this time, acquiring the districts of [[Niš]], [[Pirot]], [[Vranje]] and {{ill|Toplica (region)|lt=Toplica|sr|Toplica (oblast)}}.{{sfn|Jelavich|1983b|p=29}} In 1913 the [[Sandžak]], [[Kosovo and Metohija]] and [[Vardar Macedonia]] became part of the [[Kingdom of Serbia]], and subsequently organized into the province (''pokrajina'') of [[South Serbia (1919–22)|South Serbia]].

After the conquest of the area the Serbian government pursued a policy of forced [[Serbianisation]] which included systematic repression of [[Bulgarophiles|pro-Bulgarian]] activists.<ref>{{Google books |id=ZMyZdvTympMC |page=123 |title=Dejan Djokić, Yugoslavism: histories of a failed idea, 1918–1992 }}</ref><ref>{{Google books |id=SGnKpNf2RbAC |page=20 |title=R. J. Crampton, Eastern Europe in the twentieth century—and after }}</ref>

==Legacy==
The "Old Serbia" bank opened in [[Skopje]] in 1923 to dominate and accelerate the economy of the region.<ref>{{cite journal|url=http://scindeks.nb.rs/article.aspx?artid=1450-84869901123S}}</ref>

In Serbian historiography, the [[First Balkan War]] (1912-1913) is also known as ''War for Liberation of Old Serbia''.

