'''Sonia Harmand''' (born in 1974<ref>[https://viaf.org/viaf/197174994/ VIAF resume]</ref>) is a French archaeologist who studies [[Early Stone Age]] archaeology and the evolution of stone tool making.<ref name="auto">{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonybrook.edu/experts/profile/sonia-harmand|title=Sonia Harmand {{!}} Experts at Stony Brook University, New York|last=Communications|first=Stony Brook Office of|website=www.stonybrook.edu|language=en|access-date=2018-05-03}}</ref> She received her undergraduate degree from the University of Paris where she was associated with the "Prehistory and Technology" research unit, which was well known in the field of stone tool analysis. Harmand earned a PhD from [[Paris Nanterre University]], and is a research associate at [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|CNRS]], which is the largest French governmental research organization, and Europe's largest fundamental science agency. She worked as a Research Scientist at [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique|CNRS]] for four years before joining [[Stony Brook University]] in New York as an associate professor.<ref name="auto"/> In 2017 she was named one of the '50 Most Influential French' by the French edition of ''[[Vanity Fair (magazine)|Vanity Fair]]'' magazine.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.vanityfair.fr/classement-50-francais|title=Les 50 Français les plus influents du monde {{!}} Vanity Fair|date=2017-01-06|access-date=2018-05-04|deadurl=bot: unknown|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20170106054206/https://www.vanityfair.fr/classement-50-francais|archivedate=2017-01-06|df=}}</ref>
== Early Stone Age Archaeology ==
=== [[Lomekwi]]3 Stone Tools === In 2011, [[Sonia Harmand|Harmand]] discovered the [[Lomekwi]] 3 stone tools in the [[Turkana Basin]] of [[Kenya]] near the town of Lomewki. This discovery was made while Harmand was leading the [[West Turkana Archaeological Project]] team along with Jason Lewis. They were both working with [[Stony Brook University]]'s [[Turkana Basin Institute]] at the time <ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.turkanabasin.org/2015/05/oldest-stone-artifacts-found-in-kenya/|title=Oldest Stone Artifacts Found in Kenya's Turkana Basin|work=Turkana Basin Institute|access-date=2018-10-27|language=en-US}}</ref>.
At the [[Lomekwi]] 3 site, between 2011 and 2012, there were 149 stone artifacts recovered in total <ref name=":0">{{Cite journal|last=Lewis|first=Jason E.|last2=Harmand|first2=Sonia|date=2016-07-05|title=An earlier origin for stone tool making: implications for cognitive evolution and the transition to Homo|url=https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC4920290/|journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences|volume=371|issue=1698|doi=10.1098/rstb.2015.0233|issn=0962-8436|pmc=4920290|pmid=27298464}}</ref>. These artifacts were found at the Lomekwi 3 site which sits above the Toroto Tuff, dated at about 3.32 Ma <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/35068500/figures/4|title=Figure 4: Stratigraphic sections and placement of hominin specimens at sites in upper part of the Lomekwi drainage, west of Lake Turkana, northern Kenya.|website=www.nature.com|language=en|access-date=2018-10-27}}</ref>. The 149 artifacts range from small broken [[Lithic flake|flakes]] weighing less than 1kg to anvils and passive elements weighing about 12 kg <ref name=":1">{{Cite journal|last=Harmand|first=Sonia|last2=Lewis|first2=Jason E.|last3=Feibel|first3=Craig S.|last4=Lepre|first4=Christopher J.|last5=Prat|first5=Sandrine|last6=Lenoble|first6=Arnaud|last7=Boës|first7=Xavier|last8=Quinn|first8=Rhonda L.|last9=Brenet|first9=Michel|date=2015-05-20|title=3.3-million-year-old stone tools from Lomekwi 3, West Turkana, Kenya|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature14464#t1|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=521|issue=7552|pages=310–315|doi=10.1038/nature14464|issn=0028-0836}}</ref>. All of these tools are evidence of [[Knapping|knapped stone tools]]. Stone tool [[knapping]] was previously associated with the genus ''[[Homo]]''<ref name=":0" />. The discovery of stone tools from the [[Olduvai Gorge|Oldevai Gorge]] in [[Tanzania]] dating to about 2.6 Ma brought forth a theory of non-''[[homo]]'' [[Hominini|hominins]] usage of stone tools since there is only fossil evidence of ''[[homo]]'' from 2.4-2.3 Ma <ref name=":0" />. The tools found at [[Lomekwi]]3 are dated to ≈3.3 Ma which pushes back the evidence of stone tool use by nearly 700,000 years, and further expands the overall [[Archaeology|archaeological]] record <ref name=":1" />. Furthermore, these discoveries support the theory of usage of stone tools by non-''homo'' hominids. [[Sonia Harmand|Harmand]] and other [[Archaeology|archaeologists]] and [[Paleoanthropology|paleoanthropologists]] suspect ''[[Australopithecine|Australophithecines]]'' including: ''[[Australopithecus africanus|A. Africanus]]'', ''[[Australopithecus sediba|A. Sediba]]'', ''[[Australopithecus garhi|A. Garhi]]'', ''[[Paranthropus aethiopicus|A. Aethiopicus]]'', and ''[[Paranthropus robustus|A. Robustus]]'' to be possible non-''homo'' stone tool [[Knapping|knappers]]. The Lomekwi 3 site is still currently under excavation and the [[West Turkana Archaeological Project]] team continues fieldwork in the [[Turkana Basin]] every summer.
=== [[Acheulean]]Tools === [[Sonia Harmand|Harmand]] additionally worked along the northwest shore of [[Lake Turkana]] in [[Kenya]] in 2011, recovering and studying [[acheulean]] tools. The stone tools found at the Kokiselei 4 site are dated to about 1.76 Ma which pushes the evidence for [[acheulean]] tool use back an extra ≈300,000 years <ref name=":2">{{Cite journal|last=Lepre|first=Christopher J.|last2=Roche|first2=Hélène|last3=Kent|first3=Dennis V.|last4=Harmand|first4=Sonia|last5=Quinn|first5=Rhonda L.|last6=Brugal|first6=Jean-Philippe|last7=Texier|first7=Pierre-Jean|last8=Lenoble|first8=Arnaud|last9=Feibel|first9=Craig S.|date=September 2011|title=An earlier origin for the Acheulian|url=https://www.nature.com/articles/nature10372|journal=Nature|language=En|volume=477|issue=7362|pages=82–85|doi=10.1038/nature10372|issn=0028-0836}}</ref>. [[Acheulean]] tools are thought to be connected to ''[[Homo erectus|Homo Erectus]]'' because there were [[Homo erectus|H. erectus]] fossils found in the same area which are dated at a similar age <ref name=":2" />.
== Work at Stony Brook University == Sonia Harmand is currently an Associate Professor at New York's [[Stony Brook University]] teaching in the Anthropology Department. Along with professorial work, Harmand is an associate research scientist at the [[Centre national de la recherche scientifique]] (CNRS), and the head of the West Turkana Archeological Project (WTAP) as of 2012. Harmand's research utilizes the [[chaîne opératoire]] method to aid in her analysis of stone tools, which places emphasis on the interactions between tool-makers and their environment. The central focus of her research at Stony Brook is on the origins of hominin technology and the role of [[biomechanics]] in stone tool production. <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.stonybrook.edu/commcms/anthropology/faculty-and-staff/soniaharmand.php|title=Stony Brook University: Department of Anthropology|last=|first=|date=|website=Stony Brook University|archive-url=|archive-date=|dead-url=|access-date=October 28, 2018}}</ref>
== Honors and Publications == Harmand has received many awards for her work with [[Lower Paleolithic|Early Stone Age]] archaeology. In 2015, Harmand won both the Stone Age Institute Award for Outstanding Research into Human Origins<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.stoneageinstitute.org/2015harmand.html#.XAQcvi2ZPq1|title=2015 SAI Public Lectures: Sonia Harmand|website=www.stoneageinstitute.org|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref>, and the Field Discovery Award from the Shanghai Archaeology Forum<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.pacea.u-bordeaux1.fr/Jacques-Jaubert-et-ses.html?lang=fr|title=PACEA — De la Préhistoire à l’Actuel : Culture, Environnement et Anthropologie. - Jacques Jaubert et ses collaborateurs récompensés par l’Académie des Sciences sociales de Chine pour leurs travaux sur la grotte de Bruniquel|website=www.pacea.u-bordeaux1.fr|language=fr|access-date=2018-12-02}}</ref> for her work with the [[Lomekwi]] 3 tools. The following year, in 2016, she earned the Prix La Recherche archaeology award in Paris, France. In 2017, the Tübingen research prize for Early Prehistory and Quaternary Ecology was awarded to Harmand from the [[Eberhard Karls University|Eberhard-Karls-University]] of Tübingen, Germany.
